abstract: A weekend in the life of armed America.
snippet: A weekend in the life of armed America.
lead_paragraph: • Elliot Rodger’s parents struggled for years to engage their troubled son with the world, the Times reported yesterday. The perpetrator of the May 23 rampage in Isla Vista, Calif., was described as a high-functioning autistic child prone to depression and anxiety who once had a panic attack so severe he had to be permanently withdrawn from school. “He wasn’t just a little withdrawn,” a family friend and spokesman said. “He was as withdrawn as any person I ever met in my life.”

abstract: A guide to street fairs, parades, literary events, performances and walking tours in New York City.
snippet: A guide to street fairs, parades, literary events, performances and walking tours in New York City.
lead_paragraph: HOUSING WORKS STREET FAIR AND OTHER EVENTS (Sunday, Monday and Wednesday) Books — and the people whose lives revolve around them — are the stars of several events at this SoHo bookstore at 126 Crosby Street, near Houston Street. Thousands of donated books, records and CDs can be scooped up for $1 each at a street fair, a fund-raiser for outreach programs run by Housing Works, on Sunday from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.

abstract: Patricia Lockwood turns sexts and rape jokes and other Internet flotsam into pure poetry.
snippet: Patricia Lockwood turns sexts and rape jokes and other Internet flotsam into pure poetry.
lead_paragraph: Just before she took the microphone one soggy night in Portland, Ore., the poet Patricia Lockwood downed a shot of cheap bourbon. She had never had a drink right before a reading, but she often enacts some private joke when she speaks in public. It might be slurping her water loudly into the microphone, or rolling (instead of stepping) onto a stage, or, in this case, ingesting something that tasted to her like a puddle in a forest — anything to erase what she calls the “anxiety kegels” leading up to a performance.

abstract: A listing of discussions, film screenings, cultural activities and walking tours in New York City.
snippet: A listing of discussions, film screenings, cultural activities and walking tours in New York City.
lead_paragraph: New York Bicycle Jumble (Saturday) On the heels — or wheels — of last weekend’s TD Five Boro Bike Tour, this stationary event in Park Slope, Brooklyn, will set cyclists’ hearts racing in a different way. For the sixth year, buyers can browse new and used bicycles and accessories, as well as clothing, collectibles and other items offered by vendors from across the country. Guests can talk shop with representatives from the Bicycle Messenger Foundation; the environmental organization Times Up!; and We Bike NYC, a biking group for women. They can even take a potential purchase out for a spin. (This is the first of three such planned events in Brooklyn; the others will be in Red Hook on June 1 and Park Slope in the fall.) From 10 a.m. to 4 p.m., Old Stone House at Washington Park, Third Street, between Fourth and Fifth Avenues; nybikejumble.com; free. Squeaky wheels are welcome. (Anne Mancuso)
